Create sparse matrix representation of ratings¶

Rmat is a 6040-by-3681 sparse matrix. Its rows correspond to the unique 6040 users in the training data, and columns correspond to the unique 3681 movies in the training data (although the MovieIDs range from 1 to 3952).

In [19]:
i = paste0('u', ratings$UserID)
j = paste0('m', ratings$MovieID)
x = ratings$Rating
tmp = data.frame(i, j, x, stringsAsFactors = T)
ratings_matrix = sparseMatrix(as.integer(tmp$i), as.integer(tmp$j), x = tmp$x)
rownames(ratings_matrix) = levels(tmp$i)
colnames(ratings_matrix) = levels(tmp$j)
ratings_matrix = new('realRatingMatrix', data = ratings_matrix)

System 1: Recommendation by Genres¶

1. Genre Recommendations by highly rated¶

The top N highly-rated (based on their average ratings) by Genre among all movies that have received at least 1000 ratings.

In [21]:
get_top_rated_movies_by_genre = function(N, genre, ratings, movies, small_image_url, min_num_ratings=1000) {
    ratings %>% 
    group_by(MovieID) %>% # group ratings by movie id
    summarize(num_ratings = n(), # summarize n of ratings and averge rating for each group
            ave_ratings = round(mean(Rating), dig=3)) %>%
    inner_join(movies, by = 'MovieID') %>% # join with other movie data
    replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
    filter(num_ratings > min_num_ratings, grepl(genre, Genres)) %>% #filter movies with few ratings and filter by genre
    top_n(N, ave_ratings) %>% #get top N 
    mutate(Image = paste0('<img src="', #add image data
                        small_image_url, 
                        MovieID, 
                        '.jpg?raw=true"></img>')) %>%
    select('Image', 'Title', 'Genres', 'ave_ratings') %>% #select necessary columns
    arrange(desc(ave_ratings)) %>% #sort by average rating
    datatable(class = "nowrap hover row-border", #display data table
            escape = FALSE, 
            options = list(dom = 't',
                          scrollX = TRUE, autoWidth = TRUE))
}
In [22]:

get_most_watched_movies_by_genre = function(N, genre, ratings, movies, small_image_url) {
    ratings %>% 
    group_by(MovieID) %>% #group all ratings by movie id
    summarize(num_ratings = n()) %>% # summarize by count of ratings
    inner_join(movies, by = 'MovieID') %>% #join with other movie data
    filter(grepl(genre, Genres)) %>% #filter by specified genre
    replace(is.na(.), 0) %>% 
    top_n(N, num_ratings) %>% #get top n ratings
    mutate(Image = paste0('<img src="', #add image column
                        small_image_url, 
                        MovieID, 
                        '.jpg?raw=true"></img>')) %>%
    select('Image', 'Title', 'Genres', 'num_ratings') %>% #return necessary columns
    arrange(desc(num_ratings)) %>% #sort by num of ratings
    datatable(class = "nowrap hover row-border", #display datatable
            escape = FALSE, 
            options = list(dom = 't',
                          scrollX = TRUE, autoWidth = TRUE))
}

3. Genre Recommendation by top trending¶

The top N trending movies (based on average timestamp of ratings) by Genre. We will filter movies that have less than 50 reviews to prioritize newer ratings with sufficient review counts.

In [25]:
get_top_trending_by_genre = function(N, genre, ratings, movies, small_image_url, min_num_ratings=50) {
    ratings %>% 
    group_by(MovieID) %>% # group ratings by movie id
    summarize(num_ratings = n(), # summarize n of ratings and avg timestamp
            trending_score = round(mean(Timestamp), dig=3)) %>%
    inner_join(movies, by = 'MovieID') %>% # join with other movie data
    replace(is.na(.), 0) %>% 
    filter(num_ratings > min_num_ratings, grepl(genre, Genres)) %>% #filter movies with few ratings and filter by genre
    top_n(N, trending_score) %>% #get top N 
    mutate(
      Image = paste0(
          '<img src="', #add image column
          small_image_url,
          MovieID,
          '.jpg?raw=true"></img>'
      )
    ) %>%
    select('Image', 'Title', 'Genres', trending_score) %>% #return necessary columns
    arrange(desc(trending_score)) %>% #sort by trending score
    datatable(class = "nowrap hover row-border", #display datatable
        escape = FALSE, 
        options = list(
                dom = 't',
                scrollX = TRUE, autoWidth = TRUE
            )
    )
}

4. Genre Recommendation by Most Popular¶

The top N "popular" movies (by Genre), where popular is a linear combination of number of ratings, average rating, and average timestamp. This combination of factors will prioritize movies with a larger number of higher ratings that have been made more recently.

  • Number of Ratings tell us what movies have been most watched by users.
  • Average Rating tells us what movies have been most loved by users.
  • Average Timestamp tells us what movies have been most recently watched.

For this purpose we will define popularity as the linear combination of these three factors (addition). We will filter movies that have less than 200 reviews.

In [27]:
get_most_popular_by_genre = function(N, genre, ratings, movies, small_image_url, min_num_ratings=200) {
    ratings %>% 
    group_by(MovieID) %>% # group ratings by movie id
    summarize(
        num_ratings = n(), 
        ave_ratings = round(mean(Rating), dig=4),
        ave_ratings_timestamp = round(mean(Timestamp), dig=4),
    ) %>%
    inner_join(movies, by = 'MovieID') %>% # join with other movie data
    replace(is.na(.), 0) %>% 
    filter(num_ratings > min_num_ratings, grepl(genre, Genres)) %>% #filter movies with few ratings and filter by genre
    mutate(ave_ratings_rank = dense_rank(ave_ratings)) %>% 
    mutate(num_ratings_rank = dense_rank(num_ratings)) %>% 
    mutate(ave_ratings_timestamp_rank = dense_rank(ave_ratings_timestamp)) %>%
    mutate(
      Image = paste0(
          '<img src="', #add image column
          small_image_url,
          MovieID,
          '.jpg?raw=true"></img>'
      )
    ) %>%
    arrange(desc(ave_ratings), desc(num_ratings), desc(ave_ratings_timestamp)) %>%
    mutate(final_rank = as.double(ave_ratings_rank + ave_ratings_timestamp_rank + num_ratings_rank)) %>%
    top_n(N, (final_rank)) %>%
    select('Image', 'MovieID', 'Title', 'final_rank', 'ave_ratings_rank', 'ave_ratings_timestamp_rank', 'num_ratings_rank') %>%
    arrange(desc((final_rank))) %>%
    datatable(class = "nowrap hover row-border", #display datatable
        escape = FALSE, 
        options = list(
                dom = 't',
                scrollX = TRUE, autoWidth = TRUE
            )
    )
}
In [28]:
get_most_popular_by_genre(10,'Thriller',ratings,movies,small_image_url,200)

System 2: Collaborative Recommendation Systems¶

1. Item-based Collaborative Filtering¶

Item-based Collaborative Filtering (CF) creates recommendations based on the similarity of items in the rating matrix. The assumption behind this approach is that users will prefer movies that are similar to other movies they like.

For our purposes, similarity will be defined as Cosine Similarity

The model will create an n-x-n pairwise similarity matrix and then redcuce it a list of k most similar items for each of n items.

Recommendations are then made using these similarities to calculate the weighted sum of the user's rating for each item

Parameters

  • normalize: the metric by which to normalize the rating data in order to remove individual rating bias by users who consistently use lower or higher ratings that others. Z-score takes rating variance into account. Centering will substract the mean of the user's ratings from all their individual ratings.
  • method: The method by which to calculate the similarity between ratings by users and for items. Pearson correlation coefficient computes the correlation between two jointly distributed random variables. Cosine similarity computes the similarity between two samples.
  • k: the number of neighborhoods by which to group similar users.
In [29]:
rec_IBCF = Recommender(
    ratings_matrix, 
    method = 'IBCF',
    parameter = list(
        normalize = 'center', 
        method = 'pearson', 
        k = 100
    )
)

2. User-based Collaborative Filtering¶

User-Based Collaborative Filtering (UBCF) tries model word-of-mouth recommendations by comparing rating data from many individuals. The assumption behind this aproach os that users with similar preferences will rate items similarly. This allows us to predict missing ratings for a user by finding a neighborhood of similar users and aggregating their ratings.

The neighborhood is defined by similarity between a given number of users (k). Similarity measures commonly used are Pearson correlation coefficient and Cosine similarity.

For our purposes, similarity will be defined as Cosine Similarity

Parameters

  • normalize: the metric by which to normalize the rating data in order to remove individual rating bias by users who consistently use lower or higher ratings that others. Z-score takes rating variance into account. Centering will substract the mean of the user's ratings from all their individual ratings.
  • method: The method by which to calculate the similarity between ratings by users and for items. Pearson correlation coefficient computes the correlation between two jointly distributed random variables. Cosine similarity computes the similarity between two samples.
  • nn: the number of neighborhoods by which to group similar users.
In [34]:
rec_UBCF = Recommender(
    ratings_matrix, 
    method = 'UBCF',
    parameter = list(
        normalize = 'center', 
        method = 'pearson', 
        nn = 100
    )
)

Evalutions¶

We create an evaluation scheme which splits the ratings data into a training set (80%) and a test set (20%). For the test set, 15 items will be given to the recommender algorithm and the other items will be held out for computing the error. Additionally, all items with actual user rating of greater or equal 3 are considered positives in the evaluation process.

We will look at RMSE metrics to determine the better model. The evaluation will take place of 10 iterations (k)

In [39]:
e = evaluationScheme(ratings_matrix, method="split", train=0.8, k=10, given=15,goodRating=3)

We create two recommenders (user-based and item-based collaborative filtering) using the training data. We will choose consistent parameters between the two models for easier comparison.

  • We set normalize="center" to perform centering for the normalization.
  • We set the nearest neighborhood size to 100.
  • We use Pearson correlation (centered cosine) as a similarity measure since it treats missing ratings as "average".
  • To make a recommendation based on the models, we use the similarities to calculate a weighted sum of the user’s ratings for related items.
  • As we are interested in RMSE for the evaluation procedure, we set type="ratings" so there will not be any missing values in the realRatingMatrix after running the algorithm.
In [40]:
r1 <- Recommender(
    getData(e, "train"),
    method = 'IBCF',
    parameter = list(
        normalize = 'center', 
        method = 'Cosine', 
        k=100
    )
)
r2 <- Recommender(
    getData(e, "train"),
    method = 'UBCF',
    parameter = list(
        normalize = 'center', 
        method = 'Cosine', 
        nn = 100
    )
)

Next, we compute predicted ratings for the known part of the test data (15 items for each user) using the two algorithms.

  • We use type='ratings' so there will not be any missing values in the predicted matrix.
In [41]:
p1 <- predict(r1, getData(e, "known"), type="ratings")
p2 <- predict(r2, getData(e, "known"), type="ratings")

Finally, we can calculate the error between the prediction and the unknown part of the test data.

In [42]:
error <- rbind(
    IBCF = calcPredictionAccuracy(p1, getData(e, "unknown")),
    UBCF = calcPredictionAccuracy(p2, getData(e, "unknown"))
)

For this setup, the User-Based Collaborative Filtering model (UBCF) performs better with a smaller RSME but a slightly larger Mean Absolute Error. We will save the UBCF for use in our App.
